\par}
{\tc\tcl3 \v Windows}
To ensure that the device driver has been installed correctly:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s140\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\fs20\cgrid 
1.\tab Open the Windows Device Manager (Start->Run->compmgmt.msc, or Computer->Manage)\par
\pard\plain \s140\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\fs20\cgrid 
2.\tab Open "Ocean Optics Devices"\par
\pard\plain \s140\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\fs20\cgrid 
3.\tab Spectrometer->Properties and confirm Device Status includes "This device is working properly"\par
\pard\plain \s140\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\fs20\cgrid 
4.\tab Select the Details Tab, then select "Service" and confirm the value is "WinUSB"\par}
\par
To test SeaBreeze from a command-line environment, try building and running the provided tests and sample_code files:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s40\li0\widctlpar\adjustright \shading1000\cbpat8 \f2\fs16\cgrid   $ cd test\par
  $ make\par
  $ ./seabreeze-util --help\par
}
\par
To test SeaBreeze from a Windows GUI, build and run the "CSharpDemo" provided in sample-code.\par
To debug SeaBreeze.dll from the "CSharpDemo", edit "SeaBreezeWrapper.cs" to load your debug build of SeaBreeze.dll, then change the following line in "SeaBreezeWrapper.cs": {
\par
\pard\plain \s40\li0\widctlpar\adjustright \shading1000\cbpat8 \f2\fs16\cgrid const string DLL = @"SeaBreeze.dll";\par
}
 To the path of your debug SeaBreeze.dll, i.e.: {
\par
\pard\plain \s40\li0\widctlpar\adjustright \shading1000\cbpat8 \f2\fs16\cgrid const string DLL = @"C:\\Code\\seabreeze-code\\trunk\\SeaBreeze\\os-support\\windows\\VisualStudio2013\\x64\\Debug\\SeaBreeze.dll";\par
}
 \par}
