{{\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\adjustright \b\f1\cgrid 
SeaBreeze 2.0 Release Notes
\par}
{\tc\tcl3 \v SeaBreeze 2.0 Release Notes}
This was a significant release of SeaBreeze in that it merged the Ocean Optics "core" version of the SeaBreeze driver (used for internal projects) with the "OEM" version (sometimes called SeaBreezeOEM), which was used for external customer projects.\par
By merging the two forks back into a unified whole, this ensured that:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s140\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\fs20\cgrid 
1.\tab External OEM customers receive the "latest and greatest" updates which Ocean Optics is regularly adding for its own use; and\par
\pard\plain \s140\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\fs20\cgrid 
2.\tab Ocean Optics will be "eating its own dog food" as it were, continually testing and utilizing the same software which we provide to our OEM customers.\par}
\par
Both consequences are anticipated to benefit OEM customers over time, by improving both timeliness and robustness of future releases.\par
Key changes in SeaBreeze 2.0 for existing internal (non-OEM users) include:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
build process has been streamlined and simplified for POSIX architectures (Linux and MacOS)\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
automated Doxygen documentation has been added (see doc/)\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
a working Visual Studio solution has been added (see os-support/windows)\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
Windows device drivers have been added to the distribution\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
support for easier memory profiling has been added (see include/common/globals.h)\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
support has been added to completely destroy the {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAAJK" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 SeaBreezeWrapper}}} and DeviceFactory singletons, which had been found to generate spurious memory warnings under Visual Studio\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
a rudimentary library of sample code has been started to demonstrate how to implement basic spectral processing functions in application code, add timeouts to potentially blocking seabreeze functions (like getSpectrum), etc (see sample-code/)\par}
\par
Key changes in SeaBreeze 2.0 for existing OEM users include:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
support for RS-232 and ethernet buses has been added\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
support for the Torus has been added\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
support for the Jaz has been added\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
support for stray light coefficients has been added\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
an entirely new {\field {\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "AAAAAAAADU" }{}}{\fldrslt {\cs37\ul\cf2 SeaBreezeAPI}}} has been added, which will allow support for many powerful new capabilities in the Jaz, STS, QE65kPro, and other advanced spectrometers (see include/api/seabreezeapi)\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
previously supported spectral processing functions have been removed from the core driver, including multi-scan averaging, boxcar filters, non-linearity correction and electrical dark correction. All functions can still be implemented in application code, and we are in the process of documentating how each of these and other functions can be simply achieved (see sample-code/)\par}
\par
Additional changes will be new for all users:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
Linux udev rules have been updated to work on the latest common distributions\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
A C# GUI demonstration application has been added under sample-code/CSharpDemo. This demonstrates how to perform a number of commonly-requested basic functions, such as threaded background spectral acquisition, real-time graphing using .NET 4.0 DataVisualization, absolute irradiance calculation, how to build Windows installers, etc.\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
updated Windows device drivers have been provided for the HR2000+, Maya2000Pro, NIRQuest256, NIRQuest512, and USB2000+\par}
\par
\par}
\par}
{\bkmkstart AAAAAAABET}
{\bkmkend AAAAAAABET}
{{\pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\adjustright \b\f1\fs28\kerning28\cgrid 
Appendix B: Co-Existing with EzUSB (32-bit Windows)
\par}
{\tc\tcl2 \v Appendix B: Co-Existing with EzUSB (32-bit Windows)}
Ocean Optics supports two different USB drivers on 32-bit Windows: WinUSB (used by Ocean Optics SeaBreeze), and Cypress's ezUSB (used by Ocean Optics OmniDriver, SpectraSuite, OceanView and USB Programmer).\par
It has been found that the two drivers can coexist on the same system, although the user or a script is required to switch between one and another. This can be done manually:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s40\li0\widctlpar\adjustright \shading1000\cbpat8 \f2\fs16\cgrid     Computer -> Manage -> Device Manager -> Update Driver ->\par
        No Not This Time -> Install From a List -> Don't Search I Will Choose ->\par
            "USB2000+" (ezUSB) or "USB2000+ (WinUSB)" (SeaBreeze)\par
}
\par
Alternately, this can be scripted using the "devcon.exe" executable which comes with the WinDDK (C:/WinDDK/7600.16385.1/tools/devcon/i386). The following Cygwin transcript shows drivers for a pair of connected USB2000+ being flipped between ezUSB (OmniDriver) and WinUSB (SeaBreeze) and back again:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s40\li0\widctlpar\adjustright \shading1000\cbpat8 \f2\fs16\cgrid     $ devcon update C:\\\\WINDOWS\\\\inf\\\\oem13.inf 'USB\\Vid_2457&Pid_101e'\par
    Updating drivers for USB\\Vid_2457&Pid_101e from C:\\WINDOWS\\inf\\oem13.inf.\par
    Drivers installed successfully.\par
\par
    $ devcon update C:\\\\WINDOWS\\\\inf\\\\ooi_usb.inf 'USB\\Vid_2457&Pid_101e'\par
    Updating drivers for USB\\Vid_2457&Pid_101e from C:\\WINDOWS\\inf\\ooi_usb.inf.\par
    Drivers installed successfully.\par
}
\par
Note that the correct "oemXX.inf" driver name will be specific to your system, and can be established through something like this:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s40\li0\widctlpar\adjustright \shading1000\cbpat8 \f2\fs16\cgrid     $ devcon driverfiles '=OceanOpticsUSBDevice'\par
    USB\\VID_2457&PID_101E\\6&22194588&0&1\par
        Name: Ocean Optics USB2000+ (WinUSB)\par
        Driver installed from c:\\windows\\inf\\oem13.inf [OOIUSB_Install]. 2 file(s) used by driver:\par
            C:\\WINDOWS\\system32\\WinUSBCoInstaller.dll\par
            C:\\WINDOWS\\system32\\WdfCoInstaller01007.dll\par
    1 matching device(s) found.\par
\par
    $ devcon driverfiles '=OceanOpticsUSBDevice' | grep inf | awk '\{print $4\}'\par
    c:\\windows\\inf\\oem13.inf\par
}
\par
...or...\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s40\li0\widctlpar\adjustright \shading1000\cbpat8 \f2\fs16\cgrid     $ grep -l "Ocean Optics USB Devices" /cygdrive/c/windows/inf/*.inf | xargs cygpath -d\par
    C:\\windows\\inf\\oem13.inf\par
}
\par
Likewise, the "hardware id" which devcon expects to refer to a spectrometer model will need to be ascertained for your units. This can typically be found in the Device Manager (Properties -> Details -> Hardware IDs), or by running:\par
{
\par
\pard\plain \s40\li0\widctlpar\adjustright \shading1000\cbpat8 \f2\fs16\cgrid     $ devcon hwids '*Vid_2457*'\par
    USB\\VID_2457&PID_101E\\6&22194588&0&1\par
        Name: Ocean Optics USB2000+\par
        Hardware IDs:\par
            USB\\Vid_2457&Pid_101e&Rev_0002\par
            USB\\Vid_2457&Pid_101e\par
        Compatible IDs:\par
            USB\\Class_ff&SubClass_00&Prot_00\par
            USB\\Class_ff&SubClass_00\par
            USB\\Class_ff\par
    USB\\VID_2457&PID_101E\\6&22194588&0&2\par
        Name: Ocean Optics USB2000+\par
        Hardware IDs:\par
            USB\\Vid_2457&Pid_101e&Rev_0002\par
            USB\\Vid_2457&Pid_101e\par
        Compatible IDs:\par
            USB\\Class_ff&SubClass_00&Prot_00\par
            USB\\Class_ff&SubClass_00\par
            USB\\Class_ff\par
    2 matching device(s) found.\par
}
\par}
